 to migrate away from, ongoing subscription costs.\n\n*   **B. Content Management Systems (CMS) (Flexible, moderate learning curve):**\n    *   **Example:** **WordPress.org** (self-hosted, very popular and powerful), Joomla, Drupal.\n    *   **Pros:** Highly customizable with themes and plugins, good for blogs and complex sites, strong community support, you control your data.\n    *   **Cons:** Steeper learning curve than website builders, you need to arrange your own web hosting and domain, responsible for security and updates.\n    *   *(Note: WordPress.com is a hosted version, simpler like a website builder, but with some limitations compared to WordPress.org).*\n\n*   **C. Static Site Generators (SSGs) (For developers or those willing to learn some code):**\n    *   **Examples:** Next.js (React), Hugo (Go), Eleventy (JavaScript), Jekyll (Ruby), Gatsby (React).\n    *   **Pros:** Very fast performance, good security, often free hosting options (like Netlify, Vercel, GitHub Pages). You write content in Markdown and use templates.\n    *   **Cons:** Requires some understanding of command line, Git, and often HTML/CSS/JavaScript. Not as user-friendly for non-technical content updates.\n\n*   **D. Custom Coding (Most flexible, highest technical skill required):**\n    *   **Languages/Frameworks:**\n        *   **Frontend (what users see):** HTML, CSS, JavaScript (and frameworks like React, Vue, Angular, Svelte).\n        *   **Backend (server-side logic, databases):** Node.js, Python (Django/Flask), Ruby (Rails), PHP (Laravel), Java (Spring).\n    *   **Pros:** Complete control and flexibility, can build highly unique and complex applications.\n    *   **Cons:** Time-consuming, requires significant coding knowledge, you manage everything (hosting, security, database).\n\n**Step 3: Design and Plan Your Layout (The \"Look and Feel\")**\n\n*   **Sketch/Wireframe:** Draw a basic layout of your pages. Where will the logo go? Navigation menu? Main content? Footer?\n*   **