iate programs.\n    *   **Featured Listings:** Charge developers for premium placement.\n    *   **Advertising:** Display ads (e.g., Google AdSense).\n    *   **Premium Features:** For users or developers (e.g., advanced analytics for listed tools).\n    *   **Job Board:** For AI-related roles.\n\n**Technical Stack Considerations for a \"Boosted\" AI Tool Directory:**\n\n*   **Frontend:**\n    *   **Framework:** React, Vue, Svelte, or Next.js/Nuxt.js (for Server-Side Rendering, which is good for SEO).\n    *   **Styling:** Tailwind CSS, Material UI, Chakra UI, or custom CSS.\n*   **Backend:**\n    *   **Language/Framework:** Node.js with Express/NestJS, Python with Django/Flask, Ruby on Rails.\n    *   **Database:**\n        *   **Relational (SQL):** PostgreSQL (good for structured data, full-text search capabilities).\n        *   **NoSQL:** MongoDB (flexible schema, good if tool data structures vary wildly).\n        *   Consider a dedicated search engine like Elasticsearch or Algolia for the best search experience if the dataset grows large.\n*   **Data Collection/Scraping:**\n    *   Python with libraries like Scrapy, BeautifulSoup, Playwright/Selenium.\n*   **Deployment \u0026 Hosting:**\n    *   Vercel/Netlify (for frontend/full-stack Next.js/Nuxt.js).\n    *   Heroku, AWS, Google Cloud, Azure for backend and database.\n*   **Authentication:** Firebase Authentication, Auth0, Supabase Auth, or custom.\n\n**Steps to \"Boost\" and Build This:**\n\n1.  **MVP (Minimum Viable Product) First:**\n    *   Start with a core set of categories and manually add a decent number of well-known tools (e.g., 50-100).\n    *   Implement basic search by name and category.\n    *   Simple design, focus on usability.\n    *   Launch this to get initial feedback.\n\n2.  **Data Acquisition Strategy:**\n    *   Develop a plan for continuously finding and adding new tools.\n    *   Build the user submission form early on.\n\n3.  **Iterate on Features:**\n    *   Gradually add advanced 