            // Add active class to clicked button\n            e.target.classList.add(\u0027active\u0027);\n\n            currentFilterCategory \u003d e.target.dataset.category;\n            filterAndSearchTools();\n        }\n    });\n\n    // --- Initial Display ---\n    displayTools(aiTools); // Display all tools initially\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n**How to Use:**\n\n1.  Create a folder for your project (e.g., `ai-tool-directory`).\n2.  Inside this folder, create three files:\n    *   `index.html` (paste the HTML code)\n    *   `style.css` (paste the CSS code)\n    *   `script.js` (paste the JavaScript code)\n3.  Open `index.html` in your web browser.\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n*   **HTML (`index.html`):**\n    *   Sets up the basic page structure: header (title, search bar), main content area (filters sidebar, tool listing area), and a footer.\n    *   Links to `style.css` for styling and `script.js` for interactivity.\n    *   The `\u003cdiv id\u003d\"toolList\"\u003e` is where JavaScript will dynamically insert the AI tool cards.\n    *   The `\u003cul id\u003d\"categoryFilter\"\u003e` contains buttons for category filtering.\n*   **CSS (`style.css`):**\n    *   Provides basic styling for a clean look.\n    *   Uses Flexbox for the main layout (sidebar and content).\n    *   Uses CSS Grid for the `tool-grid` to make it responsive.\n    *   Styles the tool cards, search bar, and filter buttons.\n*   **JavaScript (`script.js`):**\n    *   **`aiTools` Array:** This is where your AI tool data is stored (for now). In a real app, this would come from a server/database. Each object has properties like `name`, `description`, `category`, `tags`, `website`, and `logo`.\n    *   **`displayTools()` function:**\n        *   Takes an array of tools.\n        *   Clears the current list.\n        *   Loops through the tools and creates an HTML \"card\" for each one.\n        *   Appends these cards to the `toolListElement`.\n    *   **`filterAndSearchTools()` function:**\n        *   This is the core logic for filtering.\n        *   It first filters by the `currentFilterCategory`.\n        *   Then, it filters by the `currentSearchTerm` (checking tool name, description, and tags).\n        *   Finally, it calls `displayTools()` with the refined list.\n    *   **Event Listeners:**\n        *   An `input` event listener on the `searchInput` calls `filterAndSearchTools()` whenever the user types.\n        *   A `click` event listener on the `categoryFilter` element (using event delegation) updates `currentFilterCategory` and calls `filterAndSearchTools()` when a category button is clicked. It also handles the \"active\" state for the category buttons.\n    *   **Initial Call:** `displayTools(aiTools)` is called once when the page loads to show all tools initially.\n\n**Next Steps to \"Boost\" This Simple Version:**\n\n1.  **More Tools:** Add many more tools to the `aiTools` array in `script.js`.\n2.  **Better Data Management:** For a large number of tools, you\u0027d move the `aiTools` data into a separate `data.json` file and fetch it using JavaScript\u0027s `fetch` API, or ideally, serve it from a backend database.\n3.  **More Advanced Filtering:** Add filters for pricing, platform, etc.\n4.  **Sorting:** Allow users to sort tools (e.g., by name, date added, popularity).\n5.  **Individual Tool Pages:** Clicking a tool could lead to a separate page (`tool-detail.html?id\u003d1`) with more information about that specific tool. This would require more advanced JavaScript routing or a multi-page setup.\n6.  **User Submissions:** Create a form for users to submit new tools (would require a backend to store submissions).\n7.  **Styling:** Greatly enhance the CSS to make it look \"top-class.\"\n8.  **AI Integration (as discussed before):** This is a much bigger step and would involve backend development and API calls to AI services.\n\nThis basic structure should give you a solid foundation to start building your AI Tool Directory!",
